Reasoning: The paper discusses a new probabilistic modelling framework based on normal factor graphs (NFGs) and their transformations. This framework has applications in information theory (e.g., linear codes), machine learning (e.g., generative models), and data science (e.g., inference algorithms). Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.IT (Information Theory), followed by cs.LG (Machine Learning), cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), cs.SI (Social and Information Networks), and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms).
